<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOME PLANES OF LEISURE AIR WIN FAA'S OK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Federal Aviation Administration said Friday that it has allowed Leisure 
Air to resume flying some of its planes, and said it would closely monitor the 
charter carrier to assure safe operations. 
</P>
<P>
 The Winston-Salem, N.C.-based scheduled and charter airline -- which serves 
Los Angeles -- suspended flights Nov. 18 after it was unable to demonstrate 
compliance with FAA safety regulations. 
</P>
<P>
 Since then, the FAA said its inspection team has worked closely with Leisure 
Air officials and has determined that the carrier may resume flying four of its 
five Airbus A-320s. It also has two DC-10s and a Boeing 757. 
</P>
<P>
 Anthony Broderick, FAA associate administrator for regulation and 
certification, said Leisure Air has made changes to meet regulations. 
</P>
<P>
 "The FAA takes its mission of ensuring the safety of the flying public most 
seriously, and will continue to closely monitor Leisure Air," Broderick said in 
a statement. 
</P>
<P>
 Leisure Air runs scheduled flights between Atlanta, Georgia, Orlando and West 
Palm Beach, Fla., Los Angeles, Boston, and Hartford, Conn. It also flies 
charters to the Caribbean, Mexico and Hawaii. 
</P>
</TEXT>
