<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY GUIDE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 SEAL BEACH 
</P>
<P>
 Mayor: George Brown 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 70 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Retired accountant 
</P>
<P>
 First elected: 1992 
</P>
<P>
 Term expires: 1996 
</P>
<P>
 Key issues: Supports using state funds to increase police patrols and improve 
city's public safety programs. Also favors reducing the utility tax, raised 
from 5% to 11% by the City Council last year as a way to cope with budget 
shortfalls. Supports strengthening enforcement of speed limits and improving 
crossing protection for students at McGaugh Elementary School, where a 
12-year-old boy was struck by a car and killed in July. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman: William J. Doane 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 73 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Retired data processing manager 
</P>
<P>
 Appointed: 1991 
</P>
<P>
 Term expires: 1998 
</P>
<P>
 Key issues: Only council member who voted against increasing the utility tax, 
calling it an unfair burden on the city's older residents. He wants to lower it 
by finding other revenue sources. Believes the best way to increase revenue 
would be to improve city's business climate. Claims city has earned a negative 
image in the business community by being too strict about development. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Councilwoman: Gwen Forsythe 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 39 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Advertising manager 
</P>
<P>
 First elected: 1990 
</P>
<P>
 Term expires: 1998 
</P>
<P>
 Key issues: Wants to maintain a family atmosphere in the city and increase 
public safety. Opposes a proposal to build more than 1,000 homes near the Bolsa 
Chica wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Councilwoman: Marilyn Bruce Hastings 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 66 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Property owner 
</P>
<P>
 First elected: 1990 
</P>
<P>
 Term expires: 1998 
</P>
<P>
 Key issues: An advocate of the city's sand-replenishment program for eroded 
beaches. Also supports locating a police substation near the beach. Has 
described herself as a slow-growth proponent, and as a representative of the 
city's Old Town area. Wants to keep a lid on the operating hours of Main Street 
businesses that sell alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman: Frank Laszlo 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 67 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Retired teacher 
</P>
<P>
 First elected: 1976 
</P>
<P>
 Term expires: 1996 
</P>
<P>
 Key issues: A controlled-growth advocate and strong opponent of the Mola 
Development Corp.'s proposal to build on the 149-acre Hellman Ranch property. 
Is concerned about traffic that may be generated by the proposed Bixby Ranch 
and golf course development on Seal Beach Boulevard but has not taken a 
position on the project. Other Key Officials 
